29
00:01:50.580 --> 00:01:55.494
Standard deviation is a measurement of
the average dispersion of values in

30
00:01:55.494 --> 00:01:58.068
a data set around their average value.

31
00:01:58.068 --> 00:02:02.790
That is how spread out the data
are from their average value.

32
00:02:02.790 --> 00:02:04.474
This is related to variance but

33
00:02:04.474 --> 00:02:09.280
it is more frequently used to describe
the average dispersion of a data set.

34
00:02:09.280 --> 00:02:14.140
The implication follows that a variance
in the highest standard deviation should

35
00:02:14.140 --> 00:02:18.480
imply lower confidence in the outputs of
a statistical forecast using the data.

36
00:02:19.490 --> 00:02:22.100
Standard deviation is
the square root of variance and

37
00:02:22.100 --> 00:02:25.270
as such, relates more directly
to the values in the dataset.

38
00:02:27.410 --> 00:02:31.370
Variance, as previously mentioned,
also measures how far

39
00:02:31.370 --> 00:02:37.010
on average a set of data values are spread
out form their average or mean.

40
00:02:37.010 --> 00:02:41.080
Higher variance in your data should
result in you being less confident and

41
00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:43.580
the accuracy of your prediction
because your data is so

42
00:02:43.580 --> 00:02:46.840
widely spread out around
their average value.

43
00:02:46.840 --> 00:02:50.870
Again, variance has the same
implication as standard deviation,

44
00:02:50.870 --> 00:02:55.070
it is simply squared to amplify
dispersion from the main value.

45
00:02:55.070 --> 00:02:58.580
Covariance is a measure of how
two variables change together.

46
00:02:59.660 --> 00:03:03.680
Covariance is not normalized, meaning
that there's no meaningful way to compare

47
00:03:03.680 --> 00:03:06.490
covariances across different variables.

48
00:03:06.490 --> 00:03:10.390
We need another measurement to compare
the way two variables change together

49
00:03:10.390 --> 00:03:12.219
in order to draw meaningful conclusions.

50
00:03:13.380 --> 00:03:18.200
Correlation provides us this normalized
measure of covariance, that is,

51
00:03:18.200 --> 00:03:20.740
how two variables change together.

52
00:03:20.740 --> 00:03:24.780
Normalization of covariance results in
a measure which we can use to meaningfully

53
00:03:24.780 --> 00:03:27.480
compare how two variables move together.

54
00:03:28.740 --> 00:03:34.469
This is a normalized measure, and so
it results in a value between -1 and

55
00:03:34.469 --> 00:03:39.780
1 and gives an objective indication of
the relationship between two variables.

56
00:03:39.780 --> 00:03:44.970
It also tells us the direction of that
relationship, positive or negative.

57
00:03:44.970 --> 00:03:50.709
Values close to zero indicate that
the relationship is not very strong.

58
00:03:50.709 --> 00:03:51.788
R-squared, or

59
00:03:51.788 --> 00:03:56.720
the coefficient of determination, is
a number that indicates the proportion

60
00:03:56.720 --> 00:04:01.741
of the variance in one variable that
is predictable from the other variable.

61
00:04:01.741 --> 00:04:06.047
A higher R squared value indicates
a better fit of our statistical

62
00:04:06.047 --> 00:04:11.650
measurement of the relationship between
the variables to the data itself.

63
00:04:11.650 --> 00:04:14.690
The definition above is important to note,

64
00:04:14.690 --> 00:04:17.980
it has a similar
interpretation as correlation

65
00:04:17.980 --> 00:04:22.220
though since it is squared the direction
of the relationship cannot be determined.

66
00:04:23.820 --> 00:04:27.240
Let's have a high level overview
now of linear regression.

67
00:04:27.240 --> 00:04:30.600
Using linear regression we
can quantify the relationship

68
00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:35.490
between changes in the independent,
or input, variable, and

69
00:04:35.490 --> 00:04:39.270
changes in the dependent,
or outcome variable.

70
00:04:39.270 --> 00:04:43.750
For example, let's look at
the relationship in the variables Y,

71
00:04:43.750 --> 00:04:48.850
X, m and B as shown on the slide below.

72
00:04:48.850 --> 00:04:55.430
We see here Y=mX+B this
relationship could be read as,

73
00:04:55.430 --> 00:05:00.130
Y is equal to m multiplied by X and
added to B.

74
00:05:00.130 --> 00:05:04.940
You may recognize this as the classic
slope intercept form of an equation for

75
00:05:04.940 --> 00:05:08.700
a straight line,
as we are all taught in algebra.

76
00:05:08.700 --> 00:05:11.390
Simple linear regression
analysis of a dataset

77
00:05:11.390 --> 00:05:15.540
may result in a similar quantified
relationship for a dataset.

78
00:05:15.540 --> 00:05:23.324
For example, our regression analysis
may result that m=3 and B=100.

79
00:05:23.324 --> 00:05:25.749
Using this quantified relationship,

80
00:05:25.749 --> 00:05:30.899
we can input values of X to predict values
of Y, which we don't have in our dataset.

81
00:05:30.899 --> 00:05:35.713
For example,
if we input a value of 100 for X,

82
00:05:35.713 --> 00:05:43.122
we can use this quantified relationship
to produce a value of 400 for Y.

83
00:05:43.122 --> 00:05:47.190
We will explore regression
analysis in a simplified example.

84
00:05:47.190 --> 00:05:51.588
First though, we must develop a thesis,
or hypothesis, for

85
00:05:51.588 --> 00:05:53.965
our forecasting relationship.

86
00:05:53.965 --> 00:05:58.434
A few additional statistical forecasting
concepts that are important to

87
00:05:58.434 --> 00:06:00.894
understand include the Y-intercept,

88
00:06:00.894 --> 00:06:05.483
which is the point where the graph
of a function, or in this case,

89
00:06:05.483 --> 00:06:11.430
the graph of our relationship between our
two variables, intersects the Y-axis.

90
00:06:11.430 --> 00:06:15.800
This is the value which cannot be
explained by our regression analysis and

91
00:06:15.800 --> 00:06:20.130
is constant despite our measured
relationship between two variables.

92
00:06:20.130 --> 00:06:24.140
This also represents the value
of our dependent variable

93
00:06:24.140 --> 00:06:26.450
when your independent
variable is equal to zero.

94
00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.100
The slope of a function is a number
that describes both the direction and

95
00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:35.400
the steepness of the line
graph of that function.

96
00:06:36.990 --> 00:06:41.120
This tells us how much we expect
our dependent variable to change

97
00:06:41.120 --> 00:06:44.110
with every one unit change
in our independent variable.

98
00:06:45.410 --> 00:06:50.411
We show two examples of two data
sets with different standard

99
00:06:50.411 --> 00:06:55.427
deviation variants, correlation,
